Notice the shift — electronic scrap overtakes regular metals because margins are 3-5x higher.

**What is inside 1 kg of circuit boards (why they are valuable):**

| Metal | Quantity per kg of boards | Value per kg of boards | % of Total Value |
|---|---|---|---|
| Copper | 200-250 grams | ₹130-165 | 5-7% |
| Gold | 0.2-0.5 grams | ₹1,400-3,500 | 50-65% |
| Silver | 1-3 grams | ₹80-250 | 3-10% |
| Palladium | 0.05-0.2 grams | ₹350-1,400 | 12-25% |
| Tin | 20-40 grams | ₹50-100 | 2-4% |
| **TOTAL recoverable value** | | **₹2,000-5,400/kg** | |

This is why circuit boards are called "urban gold mines." You are selling them at ₹1,500-2,500/kg to refiners who extract ₹2,000-5,400/kg worth of metals. In Phase 3 YOU become the refiner and capture this full value.

**Common mistake:** Not sorting electronic scrap properly. Mixed electronic scrap sells at ₹200-500/kg. But if you sort — motherboards separate, phone boards separate, connectors separate, cables separate — total value becomes ₹1,000-3,000/kg. Sorting takes 30 minutes per 10 kg and triples your money. Lazy sorting = leaving money on the table.

**One-liner:** Electronic scrap is where ₹200/kg becomes ₹2,000/kg — the same market, same effort, 10x the margin.

